consin Rapids, Wisconsin|Wisconsin Rapids]], and [[River Falls, Wisconsin|River Falls]].\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nKind was born and raised in La Crosse, the third of five children born to Greta and Elroy Kind. His is the fifth generation of his family to live in the area.<ref name=\"house.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.house.gov/kind/bio.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227075439/http://www.house.gov/kind/bio.shtml |archivedate=2009-02-27 |title=US Representative Ron Kind - Wisconsins Third Congressional District |publisher=House.gov |date=2009-02-27 |accessdate=2012-08-25}}</ref> Kind's mother formerly worked as the assistant director of personnel in the La Crosse School District. His father had a 35-year career as a telephone repairman and union leader at the La Crosse Telephone Company.<ref name=\"house.gov\"/>\n{{New Democrats}}\nKind attended the [[Public school (government funded)|public schools]] in La Crosse and became a standout student athlete at [[Logan High School (La Crosse, Wisconsin)|Logan High School]] in both football and basketball. He accepted a [[scholarship]] to [[Harvard College]], from which he graduated with honors in 1985. While attending Harvard, Kind played quarterback on the football team and worked during the summer for Wisconsin Senator [[William Proxmire]] in Washington. While working for Proxmire, he took part in investigations that helped determine the \"winners\" of the famous [[Golden Fleece Award]]s, presented by the senator to those responsible for government waste.<ref name=\"house.gov\"/>\n\nKind went on to receive a master's degree from the [[London School of Economics]] and a law degree from the [[University of Minnesota Law School]]. He practiced law for two years at the law firm of [[Quarles and Brady]] in [[Milwaukee|Milwaukee, Wisconsin]].\n\nKind returned to his hometown of La Crosse to become a county prosecutor. He later served as a special prosecutor in several counties in western Wisconsin.<ref name=\"house.gov\"/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]]'''\n**[[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Health|Subcommittee on Health]]\n**[[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Trade|Subcommittee on Trade]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*[[Congressional Wildlife Refuge Caucus]]\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n*Sportsmen's Caucus\n*Upper Mississippi River Congressional Caucus\n*[[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n*[[New Democrat Coalition]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://newdemocratcoalition-himes.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=New Democrat Coalition|date=|accessdate=6 February 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.ng911institute.org/about-the-congressional-nextgen-9-1-1-caucus|format=|publisher=Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus|date=|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Climate Solutions Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=90 Current Climate Solutions Caucus Members|author=|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus/|format=| publisher=Citizen\u00b4s Climate Lobby |date=|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nKind is the Democratic Chief Deputy [[Whip]], co-founder of both the Upper Mississippi River Congressional Caucus and the [[Congressional Wildlife Refuge Caucus]], and chair of the [[New Democrat Coalition]]. He voted with his party 87% of the time in the 112th congress and 94% of the time in the 111th congress.<ref>{{cite news|title=The U.S. Congress votes database|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/members/K000188|accessdate=August 28, 2012 | work=The Washington Post}}</ref> During the [[114th United States Congress|114th Congress]] Kind was ranked as the 19th most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives and the most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives from Wisconsin in the Bipartisan Index created by [[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]] and the [[McCourt School of Public Policy]], that ranks members of the United States Congress by their degree of bipartisanship (by measuring the frequency each member's bills attract co-sponsors from the opposite party and each member's co-sponsorship of bills by members of the opposite party).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|publisher=[[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref> Kind's work on the Subcommittee of Health has been focused primarily on health care issues within small business. As a member of the Natural Resources Committee, he has worked on the restoration of the Mississippi River and has been especially concerned about invasive species that threaten the river's ecosystem. He also concentrates on agricultural reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kind.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=2&sectiontree=2 |title=Congressman Ron Kind : About Ron |publisher=Kind.house.gov |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1998, Kind was the only Democratic congressmen from Wisconsin to vote for a House inquiry into [[impeachment of President Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bump |first1=Philip |title=For 101 members of Congress, life may soon get very awkward |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2017/05/17/for-101-members-of-congress-life-might-soon-get-very-awkward/?noredirect=on&utm_term=.4b480423c0f4 |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=20 August 2018}}</ref>\nOn October 10, 2002, Kind voted in favor of authorizing the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]].<ref>http://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/107-2002/h455</ref>\n\nKind has supported women's issues, poverty reform, veterans issues, social security, environmental issues, education, and civil rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=630#How |title=Project Vote Smart - Representative Ronald James 'Ron' Kind - Interest Group Ratings |publisher=Votesmart.org |date=2010-05-14 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>\n\nKind was the lone Wisconsin Democrat to support free trade with China, despite pressure from unions that claimed trade with China is costing jobs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ron Kind Wisconsin 2012 election center|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/campaign-2012/candidates/ron-kind-1094/|accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Ron Kind\">{{cite web|title=Ron Kind on the issues |url=http://www.ontheissues.org/house/Ron_Kind.htm|accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter the failed effort to recall Governor Scott Walker in an April 2012 vote, Kind said that Democrats should be proud of forcing recall elections despite the outcome. He said that his conversations with voters had convinced him that the only reason that Democrats lost was because people didn\u2019t think it was a proper use of the recall process.<ref>{{cite web |title=NBC 15 Madison, Wisconsin |url=http://www.nbc15.com/home/headlines/US_Rep_Ron_Kind_Applauds_Dems_for_Recall_Efforts_158267415.html|accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Positions====\n=====Childhood obesity=====\nKind and Senator [[Mark Udall]] introduced the Healthy Kids Outdoors Act, aimed at encouraging and supporting children's outdoor activities.<ref>Jackie Ostfeld. \"[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jackie-ostfeld/time-to-create-an-echo-ac_b_5654968.html Time to Create an ECHO Across America: Every Child Healthy Outdoors]\". ''Huffington Post'', August 8, 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.iwla.org/news-events/news/2011/11/03/healthy-kids-outdoors-act-supports-strategies-to-connect-kids-with-nature Healthy Kids Outdoors Act Supports Strategies to Connect Kids with Nature]\". Izaak Walton League of America, November 3, 2011.</ref>\n\nHe is the House sponsor of the FIT Kids Act, federal legislation that would require school districts to report on students' physical activity and to give youngsters health and nutritional information.<ref>{{cite web|title=NFL News |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3997041|accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Kind wrote a piece about \"the childhood obesity epidemic,\" in which he promoted both the FIT Kids Act and the Healthy Kids Outdoors Act. He said that healthy bodies lead to healthy minds, and that his FIT Kids Act would push parents and the public by requiring states and school districts to report on children's physical activity. As for the Healthy Kids Outdoors Act, it \"provides state-level incentives to develop five-year state strategies to connect children, youth and families with nature and promote outdoor recreation in communities.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Kind|first=Ron|title=Halting the childhood obesity epidemic requires support of many communities|url=http://thehill.com/special-reports/healthcare-february-2012/209277-halting-the-childhood-obesity-epidemic-requires-support-of-many-communities|accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=====Agricultural issues=====\nWhile he represents some of the country's most productive dairy farms, Kind opposes agricultural subsidies.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hubbuch|first=Chris|title=Rep. Ron Kind to eye crop subsidy reform|url=http://lacrossetribune.com/news/rep-ron-kind-to-eye-crop-subsidy-reform/article_33443bf4-48aa-11e1-b5ed-0019bb2963f4.html|accessdate=August 27, 2012}}</ref> Kind co-sponsored a bill that would have eliminated subsidies for those earning over $250,000 while increasing funding for conservation and rural development. Nancy Pelosi, who had worked to make the original bill accommodating for Democratic interests, was upset with the bill. Agricultural Committee Chairman Collin Peterson said Kind was \"a lone ranger on this, and he's dividing the caucus, and I don\u2019t appreciate it.\"  <ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Julie|title=Farm bill spurs split in Dem's ranks|newspaper=Bangor Daily News|date=July 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\n=====Trade=====\nThe ''[[La Crosse Tribune]]'' reported in January 2014 that Kind was coming \u201cunder increasing criticism from those on the left who say his support of new [[free-trade agreement]]s will kill jobs.\u201d For example, he urged fellow House members to vote for the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]]. \u201cAs a member of his district I'm frustrated with Ron Kind because I've been a supporter in the past,\u201d said activist Karli Wallace. \u201cIt's a little embarrassing to me that he seems to wants to position himself as the fig leaf of bipartisanship that can help this skate through Congress somehow.\u201d Kind also supported a measure that would allow future such deals to be negotiated without congressional involvement. \u201cIt's actually a crippling of democracy,\u201d said Bill Brockmiller, president of the Western Wisconsin [[AFL-CIO]]. \u201cWhether or not you support the TPP, [[Fast track (trade)|fast-track authority]] to a lot of people's thinking is an archaic way of passing things and an offence to democracy.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kind |first1=Ron |title=Ron Kind: Why I'm fighting for a trade deal |url=https://lacrossetribune.com/news/opinion/ron-kind-why-i-m-fighting-for-a-trade-deal/article_e71df415-ce55-5b55-b5de-aaf070b3cfdd.html |website=La Crosse Tribune |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hubbuch |first1=Chris |title=Kind under fire from left over free trade |url=https://lacrossetribune.com/news/local/kind-under-fire-from-left-over-free-trade/article_fdd14b7a-8821-5202-af78-6cfc9d1ca013.html |website=La Crosse Tribune |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Democratic National Convention]] in 2016, Kind was scheduled to speak to a group of Wisconsinites when he was silenced by protesters from his state who opposed his support of the Trans Pacific Partnership trade deal. \u201cThere's confusion; people are conflating trade with trade agreements,\u201d Kind insisted. \u201cThe trade that's going on absent trade agreements has not worked well for us: China, Brazil, India. We don't have trade agreements with those countries.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sommerhauser |first1=Mark |title=At national convention, Ron Kind faces flack on TPP |url=https://www.winonadailynews.com/news/local/at-national-convention-ron-kind-faces-flack-on-tpp/article_e5047ca7-bffc-5bbe-9498-44eae586edb8.html |website=Winona Daily News |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====Gun control=====\nUp through and during the 2012 campaign, Kind opposed any form of enhanced gun control, but after the Sandy Hook massacre he seemed to be open to it, saying, \u201cWe\u2019re going to have to have a discussion while also keeping in mind the concerns of law-abiding, safety-conscious gun owners in America.\u201d He added, \u201cI just don\u2019t see where armed guards or teachers with guns in our schools means freedom for our children.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hubbuch |first1=Chris |title=Walz, Kind weigh in on gun rights, school safety |url=https://www.winonadailynews.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/walz-kind-weigh-in-on-gun-rights-school-safety/article_4104f764-5acf-11e2-9b4f-001a4bcf887a.html |website=Winona Daily News |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[WIZM (AM)|WIZM]] reported in February 2018 that Kind was one of a relatively small number of Democrats who had received contributions from the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]]. Since 2009, he had accepted $7,950 in from various NRA political action committees. He had also collected $5,400 from the Connecticut-based [[National Shooting Sports Foundation]], which calls itelf \"The Firearms Industry Trade Association.\" The NRA endorsed Kind in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=La Crosse's Ron Kind among the recipients of gun lobby contributions |url=http://www.1410wizm.com/index.php/home-m/item/32732-la-crosse-s-ron-kind-among-the-recipients-of-gun-lobby-contributions |website=WIZM |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====Muslim ban=====\nWhen then-presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]] called in 2015 for temporarily banning all Muslims from entering the United States, Kind said Trump was \u201cplaying in the same huddle as ISIS\u201d and was making [[ISIS]] recruiting easier by playing into the terrorist group's narrative.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lindquist |first1=Eric |title=FRONT PAGE Kind rejects growing call for U.S. troops to fight IS |url=http://www.leadertelegram.com/News/Front-Page/2015/12/15/Kind-rejects-U-S-troops-to-fight-IS.html |website=Leader-Telegram |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Kind issued a statement in which he maintained that \u201cPresident Trump's Executive Order blocking refugees and people from select Muslim countries from entering the United States does not reflect who we are as a nation. We cannot start discriminating based on religion. Instead of helping keep our country safe it will jeopardize our national security by giving ISIS and other terror groups another recruitment tool and making it harder for our allies in Muslim nations to work with us on counter-terrorism operations.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Weigel |first1=David |title=Democratic lawmakers from states and districts won by Trump oppose travel ban |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/01/30/democratic-lawmakers-from-states-and-districts-won-by-trump-oppose-travel-ban/?utm_term=.60b3be00ccdc |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====Student aid=====\nIn 2010, Kind supported the [[Student Aid and Fiscal Responsibility Act]].<ref>{{cite web |title=FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 718 |url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll718.xml |website=H R 3221      RECORDED VOTE |publisher=clerk.house.gov |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====Tax=====\nOn October 20, 2017, Kind rejected tax cuts, questioning their ability to invigorate the economy.<ref name=\"WPTV\">{{cite web |title=U.S. Rep. Ron Kind Discusses Taxes, Healthcare, Immigration |url=https://wpt.org/here-and-now/us-rep-ron-kind-discusses-taxes-healthcare-immigration |website=Wisconsin Public Television |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====Health care=====\nKind supported [[Obamacare]], denying at a public event that insurers were cancelling insurance. Rather, they were signing customers up \u201cwith new plans that are compliant with ACA.\u201d He insisted that under five percent of the population would lose their insurance under Obamacare and that most would \u201cget a much better deal in the healthcare exchange - good price and much better benefits than what they were paying before.\u201d He added that young people are \u201cprobably going to get a real good deal\u201d under Obamacare.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lyon |first1=Barbara |title=Kind: Health care reform can work |url=https://chippewa.com/news/local/kind-health-care-reform-can-work/article_924da201-d2ea-59a5-b684-f74d52567575.html |website=The Chippewa Herald |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nKind voted against the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|2017 Republican health-care bill]]. \"I thought it was a bad piece of legislation,\u201d he said, \u201cboth in the process of how it came together and the impact it will have for people back home.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cuevas |first1=Jason |title=Kind: Health care bill 'a bad piece of legislation' |url=https://www.wiscnews.com/juneaucountystartimes/news/local/kind-health-care-bill-a-bad-piece-of-legislation/article_3ac293c3-8179-5aa3-aff2-9bc4f3a8dc93.html |website=Juneau Star-Times |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====Immigration=====\nIn October 2014, Kind said he supported \u201ccomprehensive immigration reform that secures our borders, helps our farmers and businesses meet their labor needs, and fairly addresses the millions of undocumented individuals in the shadows.\"<ref name=\"Kurtz, Kind\">{{cite web |title=Kurtz, Kind answer questions |url=https://lacrossetribune.com/kurtz-kind-answer-questions/article_35581f35-1080-5fcc-af19-d4eb905702a5.html |website=La Crosse Tribune |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 20, 2017, Kind spoke up for [[DACA]], saying that the so-called Dreamers \u201care as American as anyone else's children.\"<ref name=\"WPTV\" />\n\n=====Environment=====\nIn October 2017, Kind announced a plan to protect the [[Mississippi River]]. It involved \u201cfour main parts: creating jobs by supporting recreation, tourism and navigation; maintaining railroad safety; supporting the Mississippi River Restoration Program; and promoting the 'Conservation on the Farm' bill.<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Rep. Ron Kind unveils plan to protect Mississippi River |url=https://www.news8000.com/news/us-rep-ron-kind-unveils-plan-to-protect-mississippi-river/640206445 |website=WKBT-TV |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====Iraq=====\nIn October 2002, Kind voted to authorize the use of military force in Iraq. He later regretted that vote: \u201cIt was the wrong war at the wrong time for the wrong reason,\u201d Kind explained.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hubbuch |first1=Chris |title=CAMPAIGN PROFILE: ROn Kind |url=https://lacrossetribune.com/courierlifenews/news/local/govt-and-politics/elections/campaign-profile-ron-kind/article_817b8e2e-1558-5440-b6f5-214327bb45c4.html |website=La Crosse Tribune |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a January 2007 letter to President Bush, Kind and a dozen-odd other Members of Congress wrote that success in Iraq \u201crequires regional cooperation and positive engagement from all neighboring states. The history of the Middle East is too vast, too complex and too tumultuous to expect progress without an integrated diplomatic effort and multinational support from all of Iraq's neighbors. History is replete with centuries of marked violence and failed crusades, perpetrated by ignorance, arrogance and dogma.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hay Brown |first1=Matthew |title=Gilchrest calls on Bush to open talks |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2007-01-13/news/0701130346_1_gilchrest-iran-syria |website=The Baltimore Sun |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Berman |first1=Howard |title=Letter to President George W. Bush |url=https://votesmart.org/public-statement/315785/letter-to-president-george-w-bush#.W4R64ehKiM8 |website=Vote Smart |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====ISIS and Syria=====\nIn September 2014, Kind said that he opposed \u201csending any military combat troops in order to deal with ISIS,\u201d but expressed support for President Obama's \u201cdecisions to use targeted airstrikes in Syria and Iraq to degrade and destroy [[ISIS]], and to send service members to assist Iraqi and [[Kurds|Kurdish]] forces with training and intelligence.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Rep. Ron Kind Statement on the Obama Administration's ISIS Strategy |url=https://kind.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-ron-kind-statement-obama-administrations-isis-strategy |website=kind.house.gov |accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====VA Hospitals=====\nKind announced in May 2014 that he would ask for the establishment of an independent bipartisan commission to investigate conditions at [[Veterans Health Administration|VA hospitals]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tighe |first1=Mike |title=Kind 'mad as hell,' wants bipartisan panel to probe VA |url=https://lacrossetribune.com/news/local/kind-mad-as-hell-wants-bipartisan-panel-to-probe-va/article_a649f448-f40d-5d67-86a7-69dbdeadbb64.html |website=La Crosse Tribune |accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====Medical marijuana=====\nKind has said he supports legalizing medical marijuana but opposes \u201cthe full legalization of recreational marijuana.\"<ref name=\"Kurtz, Kind\" />\n\n=====Child labor=====\nIn February 2012, Kind applauded the [[U.S. Department of Labor]] for agreeing to re-examine a proposed rule that would prohibit children from working on family farms. \u201cThese rules would create an unnecessary burden on our family farmers,\u201d said Kind. \u201cThey dont make sense and dont take into account the way our family farms operate.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Kind Applauds Administration's Dismissal of Proposed Child Labor in Agriculture Rule |url=https://kind.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/kind-applauds-administrations-dismissal-proposed-child-labor-agriculture |website=kind.house.gov |accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Kind introduced a bill that would prohibit the import of goods made by child labor, slave labor, or forced labor. \u201cThe United States must be a leader in elevating labor standards around the world. As a nation, it's critical that we stand united against exploitative labor practices in any country,\u201d said Kind.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rep. Ron Kind Introduces Bill to Stop Child Labor Overseas |url=https://kind.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-ron-kind-introduces-bill-stop-child-labor-overseas |website=kind.house.gov |accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political campaigns==\n===1996===\nKind was first elected to represent {{ushr|Wisconsin|3}} in November 1996. In September 1995, he had announced his intention to run for the 3rd Congressional District seat being vacated by 16-year incumbent [[Steve Gunderson]]. Kind later won a five-way race for the Democratic nomination and went on to defeat his [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] opponent, [[James Harsdorf]], 52 percent to 48 percent, becoming only the third Democrat to represent this district in the 20th century and only the second in 88 years. Kind didn't face another contest nearly that close until 2010.\n\n===1998===\nHe beat Republican Troy Brechler in 1998 with 128,256 votes to Brechler's 51,001.<ref>{{cite web |title=STATISTICS OF THE CONGRESSIONAL ELECTION |url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/1998/98Stat.htm |website=clerk.house.gov |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2000===\nKind defeated Susan Tully (R) in the general election, 64% to 36%.<ref>{{cite web |title=STATISTICS OF THE CONGRESSIONAL ELECTION |url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/2000election.pdf |website=clerk.house.gov |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2002===\nIn the 2002 election, Bill Arndt, the Republican, received 69,955 votes, Kind received 131,038, and Jeff Zastrow, Libertarian, received 6,674.<ref>{{cite web |title=STATISTICS OF THE CONGRESSIONAL ELECTION |url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/2002election.pdf |website=clerk.house.gov |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2004===\nIn 2004 he beat Republican Dale W. Schultz, who received 157,866 votes to Kind's 204,856.<ref>{{cite web |title=STATISTICS OF THE CONGRESSIONAL ELECTION |url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/2004election.pdf |website=clerk.house.gov |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2006===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Wisconsin, 2006#3rd Congressional District}}\nIn 2006 he defeated [[Paul R. Nelson]] with 65 percent of the vote.\n\nIn the 2006 election for Kind's seat, the main difference between Kind and his primary challenger, Chip DeNure, was \u201cwhether to set a timetable for withdrawing American troops from Iraq.\u201d A majority of Americans, like DeNure, supported a timetable. DeNure believed the 9/11 attacks were \u201can inside job by terrorists within the U.S. government.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Magney |first1=Reid |title=Kind\u2019s stance on war in Iraq inspires DeNure\u2019s campaign |url=https://lacrossetribune.com/community/couleecourier/election/kind-s-stance-on-war-in-iraq-inspires-denure-s/article_b19c3c6f-3b53-53bf-a4e7-2ffa8f2e0db3.html |website=Coulee Courier |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2008===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Wisconsin, 2008}}\nIn 2008 he won with 63 percent of the vote.\n\n===2010===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Wisconsin, 2010}}\nIn late 2009, Kind considered running for governor of Wisconsin in 2010 but ultimately said that instead, he would push in Congress for health-care reform. \u201cMy first responsibility must be to get affordable and accessible health care reform passed this year for all Wisconsin families,\u201d he said. \u201cThat is why I cannot run for governor. I have a responsibility and duty to the people of Wisconsin to continue work on the health care reform agenda ahead of us.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Kind won't run for Wisconsin governor |url=http://archive.jsonline.com/news/milwaukee/61103647.html/ |website=Wisconsin State Journal |publisher=AP |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> The ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'' reported, however, that he had given up on running for governor \u201cafter a poll showed that few Wisconsinites knew him.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Umhoefer |first1=Dave |title=Eyes on Barrett as Kind opts out of governor's race |url=http://archive.jsonline.com/news/statepolitics/61383067.html/ |website=Journal Sentinel |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, local media described Kind as facing \u201cwhat is widely considered his toughest re-election challenge.\u201d His Republican opponent, state Sen. [[Dan Kapanke]], \u201cfocused almost exclusively on three core GOP issues - less spending, lower taxes and smaller government.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lindquist |first1=Eric |title=Kind's toughest challenge |url=http://www.leadertelegram.com/News/Front-Page/2010/10/24/Kind-s-toughest-challenge.html |website=Leader-Telegram |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nHis opponent, Kapanke, criticized Kind for allegedly solicing thousands of dollars in 2007 from a group of [[Eau Claire, Wisconsin|Eau Claire]] doctors.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lindquist |first1=Eric |title=Rep. Kind wins tight contest |website=Leader-Telegram}}</ref>\n\nHe defeated Kapanke with 50 percent of the vote.\n\n===2012===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Wisconsin, 2012#District 3}}\nThere was talk that Kind might run for the U.S. Senate in 2012 to replace the retiring [[Herb Kohl]], but he decided not to mount a primary challenge to [[Tammy Baldwin]], who had already announced a senate run.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Rebecca|title=Rep. Ron Kind declines senate bid|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2011/09/15/rep-ron-kind-declines-senate-bid/|accessdate=August 26, 2012|work=CNN|date=September 15, 2011}}</ref> There was also a push to draft Kind to run for governor in 2012 against Scott Walker.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kind, Obey avoid confirming recall petition signatures|url=http://www.wxow.com/story/16481255/some-potential-candidates-in-recall-delay-signing-petition|accessdate=August 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nKind ultimately decided to run for reelection in the 3rd district. He faced retired U.S. Army Col. [[Ray Boland]] in the November election and won.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shuda|first=Nathaniel|title=U.S. Reps. Paul Ryan, Ron Kind share diverging viewpoints during Wood County visits|url=http://www.wisconsinrapidstribune.com/article/20120810/WRT010403/208100432?odyssey=mod{{!}}mostcom&nclick_check=1 |accessdate=August 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nKind beat GOP challenger Tony Kurtz, 56% to 43%.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wisconsin's 3rd Congressional District elections, 2014 |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Wisconsin%27s_3rd_Congressional_District_elections,_2014 |website=Ballotpedia |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nKind beat Myron Buchholz, 81% to 19%, in the primary, and faced no challenger in the general election.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wisconsin's 3rd Congressional District elections, 2014 |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Wisconsin%27s_3rd_Congressional_District_election,_2016 |website=Ballotpedia |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' reported that Kind was a \u201cprime target\u201d in the 2018 election. He was viewed by the GOP as \u201ca creature of Washington.\"<ref name=\"Hill shift\">{{cite web |last1=Kamisar |first1=Ben |title=Lawmakers targeted as district politics shift |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/330778-lawmakers-targeted-as-district-politics-shift |website=The Hill |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Kind's primary opponent Juliet Germanotta was arrested in New York City on an outstanding warrant for grand theft. She had bought a $4,800 ring from a jewelry store, then received a full refund after returning a less valuable ring.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chicago Sun-Times Backs Lipinski |url=https://www.nationaljournal.com/s/664123/chicago-sun-times-backs-lipinski |website=National Journal |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKind and his wife, Tawni, live in his hometown of La Crosse. She is an official court reporter for the County Court system. They have two sons, Johnny (born in August 1996) and Matthew (born in May 1998). They are members of Immanuel Lutheran Church ([[Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.facebook.com/pg/repronkind/about/ |title=Congressman Ron Kind : About Ron |publisher=Facebook.com |accessdate=2018-09-29}}</ref>\n\nKind is a member of the La Crosse Optimists Club, a leader in the [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys and Girls Club]], and the La Crosse [[YMCA]]. He is also on the board of directors for Coulee Council on Alcohol or Other Drug Abuse. His wife organizes the annual Congressional Art Competition for high school artists in western Wisconsin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ronkind.org/News.cfm |title=Elect Ron Kind for Congress - Wisconsin Third Congressional District |publisher=Ronkind.org |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Rangel ethics probe===\nIn October 2009, ''The Hill'' profiled Kind, focusing on his challenge to \u201cthe Democratic status quo.\u201d While calling him \u201can influential voice on...ethics,\u201d The Hill also noted that Kind had refused to join in the effort that year to have [[Ways and Means Committee|Ways and Means]] Chairman [[Charles Rangel]] (D-N.Y.) step down amid an ethics probe involving Rangel's taxes. \u201cWe're all ultimately human and none of us are perfect and we're all prone to mistakes from time to time,\u201d Kind had explained. \u201cIf that becomes that new standard - that any mistake is subject to dismissal or losing their position - then that's going to be a very tough standard for each and every member to have to live up to.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crabtree |first1=Susan |title=Killing them with Kind-ness: Rep. Kind uses diplomacy to challenge leaders |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/64873-killing-them-with-kind-ness-rep-kind-uses-diplomatic-approach-to-challenge-leaders |website=The Hill |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Pay-for-talk controversy===\nIn October 2010, two doctors at the OakLeaf Surgical Hospital in Eau Claire charged that Kind had demanded campaign donations before meeting them to discuss the Children's Health and Medical Protection Act. Kind denied the accusation. One of the accusers, a surgeon who requested anonymity, asserted in a sworn statement that a Kind aide explained that he \u201ctypically requires a contribution of $10,000 for a one- to two-hour personal meeting and $25,000 for a half-day meeting.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bice |first1=Daniel |title=Political mystery unfolds in Western Wisconsin |url=http://archive.jsonline.com/watchdog/noquarter/105739908.html/ |website=Milwaukee-Wisconsin Journal Sentinel |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Failure to respond to ex-Marine===\nIn 2017 he was criticized for his failure to respond to an ex-Marine who committed suicide after calling Kind's Washington office for help and having received none.<ref name=\"Hill shift\" />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Further reading cleanup|date=February 2014}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=k000188 | votesmart=630 | fec=H6WI03099 | congress=ron-kind/1498 }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928014805/http://www.wisdems.org/index.php?display=CandidateDetails&id=246238 Profile] at the Democratic Party of Wisconsin (archived)\n\n==External links==\n*[https://kind.house.gov Congressman Ron Kind] official U.S. House website\n*[http://www.ronkind.org/ Ron Kind for Congress] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Wisconsin/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Ron_Kind_%5BD-3%5D/}}\n*{{C-SPAN|ronkind}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steve Gunderson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Wisconsin|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Wisconsin's 3rd congressional district]]|years=1997\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=???}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[New Democrat Coalition]]|years=2001\u20132005|alongside=[[Jim Davis (Florida politician)|Jim Davis]], [[Adam Smith (politician)|Adam Smith]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ellen Tauscher]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joseph Crowley|Joe Crowley]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[New Democrat Coalition]]|years=2013\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Himes]]}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kay Granger]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=63rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim McGovern (U.S. politician)|Jim McGovern]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{WI-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCu